The model is simple: CSArt Ottawa curates a season of Ottawa-based artists; patrons purchase a subscription; the money is shared amongst the artists; the artists make original works for all of the subscribers; we throw a party about it.Want in? Let’s do this.Season AnnouncementAnnouncing our 2016-2017 Season Artists:The PepTides, rocking pop 9-piece band with a funky performance style, October 17-23, 2016THUNK! Theatre, performance duo working in community connection, November 21-26, 2016Mark B. Stephenson, painter and maker joining tech with technique, February 12-18, 2017Susie Osler, nature-inspired ceramic artist with an eye for environment, April 1-7, 2017Chris Turnbull, experimental poet bringing words to new places, May 22-27, 2017Go to csartottawa.ca for project details.What You Get:Subscribers of the 2016-2017 Season will receive:
Five original, limited-edition works of art from the season’s artists delivered throughout the year, including tickets for two to an exclusive concert and a live theatre show, a painting, a piece of ceramic art, and a book of poetry (see season announcement for details);
Exclusive event invites for food, drink, and artistic merriment;
Insider access to the creative process, meeting the artists and getting in on the creation ground floor;
The joy of making cool stuff happen in Ottawa.
PLUS, subscribe now through our Indiegogo for:
No HST --save $52!
A free CSArt T-Shirt 
Other PerksGive to our campaign and get art teasers from our season’s artists. Ceramics from Susie, drawings from Mark, songs from the Peptides, QT with THUNK! Theatre, and poetry from Chris will give you a taste of what’s in store for CSArt Ottawa 2016-2017.Or, sport your Ottawa pride with our sweet new t-shirts, Ottawa (de)tours tickets, or a stylized print of Ottawa from The Most Canada.What We Need CSArt Ottawa aims to be a fully self-sustaining initiative, with no need for outside funding once we’ve formed a strong subscriber base. All we need is a little boost to get off the ground. That's why early subscriptions are so important. 1) SubscriptionsSupport early, and make CSArt Ottawa a reality. Keep your finger on the pulse of the Ottawa arts scene by letting CSArt Ottawa keep you up to date on who’s moving and shaking in our community. Get 5 original, limited editions art works per year, access to exclusive arts events, and opportunities to meet the artists. If we can get 20 early subscribers by the end of this campaign ($8000), then we can get a move on making our first season as amazing as possible. Every subscription counts.2) Supply Fund Our goal is to pay artists for their work: their creative ideas, and the time and sweat it takes to make them happen. So how do we make that possible for the art forms that cost a lot to produce (theatre, music), paying those artists the same as those in art forms that cost less to produce (writing, storytelling)? We created the Supply Fund to answer that question. Our season's artists can access the CSArt Supply Fund to help level the playing field. We aim to have a supply fund starter of $1200 by the end of this campaign. The more we have in our Supply Fund, the more diverse art forms we can support --and as Canada's first multi-disciplinary community-supported art project, that's really important to us. The ImpactDo you reject the idea that Ottawa is boring? Good. So do we.There’s a gap separating artists and patrons in Ottawa. Let’s close it, let’s recognize our artists as important contributors to our city, let’s build community, and let’s have a hell of a good time doing it.CSArt Ottawa will pay artists to create original work, make this work accessible to patrons, and add to the great stuff happening in our city. TeamMegan Piercey Monafu is an Ottawa-based artist who makes things happen. With a diverse background in writing, directing, facilitating, community development, and start-ups, Megan has the connections and skills to get this off the ground and to shine a spotlight on Ottawa’s arts community.But she won’t do it alone --the CSArt Advisory Committee is there to help, with skills in marketing, outreach, finance, event planning, web design, and more. With a full leadership team of 6 plus a first season involving 14 of Ottawa’s finest artists, CSArt Ottawa is set to knock yer socks off.Risks & ChallengesArtists are risky people. It’s true. They set out with a seed of an idea and a little pocket change, and who knows what they’ll end up creating.Patrons are risky too. Audiences change their minds all the time about whether or not they like an artist, and artists spend a lot of time and energy trying to figure out what will entertain and touch their patrons.We want to build a relationship of trust and respect between artists and patrons, providing patrons with a way to support artists financially and artists a new way to connect with patrons. Together, we share in the risk of the creation process. But, we also share in whatever awesome stuff comes out of it.Why are the subscriptions so damn expensive?It’s a challenge of our initiative: providing enough cash to artists that they can create original work for all of our subscribers, while still being financially accessible to subscribers. The money spent on subscriptions goes to the artists’ labour, the event planning, the supplies, and getting the art to you.Think of this way: if last year you bought 2-3 pieces of art, 2 tickets to a live concert, and 2 tickets to a theatre performance, you probably spent at least $400 all told. We’re asking you to take the leap of spending that money up front, and then have all these things provided to you throughout the year. That means all your money stays in Ottawa, supporting our local economy, with the added bonus that the art is designed specifically with you in mind. About Community-Supported Art:Community-Supported Art is modeled after the Community-Supported Agriculture (or ‘farm share’) model of food distribution, where customers deal directly with farmers, investing funds at the beginning of the growing season. This upfront investment allows the farmers to create a harvest of healthy, organic, and local food, which is delivered to customers on a weekly basis throughout the harvest. Everyone shares in the inherent risk of farming as well as in the bounty of a good harvest, and buyers are more connected to their food, to the natural season, and to the local economy.The first CSArt project was created by Springboard for the Arts in St. Paul, Minnesota, and has since been replicated across the US as well as in Hamilton/Burlington, ON and Montreal, QC.CSArt Ottawa aims to take the best from the existing models and create a new, multidisciplinary platform --the first of its kind in Canada. Our subscribers will fund and receive work from artists in the Ottawa region, and Ottawa artists will connect with new audiences. Just as participation in Community-Shared Agriculture provides healthy, local food and a greater understanding of the local farming process, participation in our CSArt season will provide exciting local works and a greater understanding of the process and individual artists.Sharing is CaringWe get that you can’t give to every cool crowd-funding thing that comes your way, no matter how good the perks. Sharing this campaign on your social media and with your friends is still a huge help to us. Let Ottawa know that a great new thing is coming its way!
